# RFC-007 — Security, Privacy & Trust

**Status:** Accepted
**Version:** 1.0.0
**Author:** Atlas AI Founding Team
**Date:** July 22, 2026

---

# 1. Purpose

This RFC defines Atlas' security, privacy and trust principles.

Atlas handles highly sensitive personal information.

Security is not an additional feature.

Security is part of the product.

Every engineering decision must consider confidentiality, integrity, availability and transparency.

---

# 2. Security Philosophy

Atlas assumes that every user document may contain highly sensitive information.

Every component must be designed following the principle of least privilege.

Only the minimum necessary information should be collected, processed and stored.

---

# 3. Privacy by Design

Privacy is implemented from the first line of code.

Atlas shall:

- collect only necessary information;
- minimize stored personal data;
- encrypt sensitive information;
- allow users to control their own data;
- explain how information is used.

---

# 4. Trust Principles

Atlas commits to:

- honesty;
- transparency;
- explainability;
- accountability;
- legal compliance.

The platform must never create false certainty.

Whenever uncertainty exists, Atlas must clearly communicate it.

---

# 5. Authentication

All private resources require authentication.

Recommended methods:

- Email + Password
- Google
- Apple
- Microsoft

Future support:

- Passkeys
- Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)

---

# 6. Authorization

Users may only access their own information.

Internal services receive only the permissions strictly necessary.

Administrative access must be auditable.

---

# 7. Encryption

Sensitive information must be encrypted:

During transmission:

- TLS

At rest:

- Database encryption
- Object Storage encryption

Passwords must never be stored in plain text.

Only secure password hashing algorithms are permitted.

---

# 8. Document Protection

Uploaded documents require additional protection.

Requirements:

- encrypted storage;
- secure access URLs;
- access expiration;
- malware scanning (future);
- immutable original copy.

Atlas never modifies original documents.

Derived files are stored separately.

---

# 9. AI Privacy

AI providers receive only the information necessary to complete a task.

Whenever possible:

- remove unnecessary identifiers;
- minimize transmitted data;
- separate documents from identity.

Atlas should support replacing AI providers without exposing unnecessary user information.

---

# 10. Auditability

Every critical action generates an audit record.

Examples:

- login;
- document upload;
- recommendation generated;
- recommendation updated;
- permission changes;
- administrative actions.

Audit logs must never be editable.

---

# 11. Legal Updates

Whenever legislation changes:

Atlas records:

- previous recommendation;
- updated recommendation;
- legal justification;
- effective date;
- affected users.

Atlas never silently changes guidance.

---

# 12. User Control

Users have the right to:

- view stored information;
- update personal information;
- download their data;
- request account deletion (where legally applicable);
- understand why information is requested.

---

# 13. Incident Response

Security incidents require:

- immediate investigation;
- impact assessment;
- user notification when legally required;
- corrective actions;
- permanent documentation.

Every incident should generate internal lessons learned.

---

# 14. AI Safety

Atlas AI must never:

- invent legal requirements;
- fabricate official sources;
- hide uncertainty;
- impersonate government authorities;
- make decisions on behalf of users.

The final decision always belongs to the user.

---

# 15. Data Retention

Data should be retained only as long as necessary.

Archived Cases remain available until:

- user deletion request;
- legal retention period expires;
- regulatory requirements change.

---

# 16. Compliance

Atlas should be designed to support compliance with:

- GDPR
- LGPD
- future international privacy regulations.

Compliance should be considered during architecture, not after deployment.

---

# 17. Internal Engineering Rules

Developers must never:

- hardcode secrets;
- expose credentials;
- log sensitive personal information;
- bypass authentication;
- disable security checks in production.

Secrets must be stored using secure secret management.

---

# 18. Trust Communication

Whenever Atlas generates an important recommendation, users should always be able to see:

- why the recommendation exists;
- supporting evidence;
- official sources;
- date of the legal information;
- recommendation history.

Trust increases when information is explainable.

---

# 19. Golden Rule

Atlas protects people before protecting software.

Whenever a conflict exists between convenience and user safety, safety takes priority.

---

# Decision Summary

Security, privacy and transparency are core characteristics of Atlas.

They are not optional features.

Every future Atlas product must inherit these principles.

